ivate reciprocity-a cooperative action marked by the mutual exchange of favors and services-and informally seek aid and connection with their transnational diaspora community. Using surveys conducted with Palestinians throughout the diaspora, interviews with those inside the Nahr al Bared Refugee camp in Lebanon, and data pulled from online community spaces, these findings push back against the cynical idea that online organizing is fruitless, emphasizing instead the productivity of these digital networks.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-SA 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aCooperationzLebanon. 0aEmigrant remittanceszLebanon. 0aInformation technologyxSocial aspectszLebanon. 0aRefugees, Palestinian ArabxSocial networkszLebanon. 0aRefugees, Palestinian ArabzLebanonxEconomic conditions. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Refugees.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311073915240uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520383258zOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520383258zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520383258/original  a978-3-11-073915-2 University of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA